<DOC><DOCNO> AP891002-0324 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2027EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Coke-Columbia     10-02 0224</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Coke-Columbia,0232</SECOND><HEAD>Coke Board Approves Columbia Sale to Sony</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Coca-Cola Co.'s board of directors on Mondayapproved the sale of its stock in Columbia Pictures EntertainmentInc. to Sony Corp. and said it would use the money _ $1.45 billion_ for its soft drink operations and buying back some of its ownstock.   The Coca-Cola board gave its formal OK to the sale of thecompany's 53.8 million shares of Columbia Pictures to Sony USAInc., a subsidiary of the Sony Corp. The board also authorized thepurchase of up to 20 million shares of Coca-Cola stock through 1991.   The deal will bring Coke an after-tax gain of some $530 million,or $1.53 per share, this year, the company said.   Sony reached an agreement to buy Columbia last week, with Sonypaying $27 a share, for a total cost of $3.4 billion. At thatprice, Coke's take comes to $1.45 billion.   Coke entered the movie business in 1982, when it bought apredecessor of Columbia.   ``Our investment in the entertainment business has providedsubstantial value and outstanding returns to our shareholders,''Coca-Cola Chairman Roberto C. Goizueta said in a statement. ``Wesee excellent opportunities to continue to build ... through growthof and further investments in our worldwide soft drink business,and by instituting a new share repurchase program.''</TEXT></DOC>